Q: How to change Class&#39;s Prototype in ES6 A: <p>If this is for your own code, rather than &quot;trying to mess with page code you didn't write&quot;, then the trick is to not use your actual class, but to use <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Proxy" rel="nofollow noreferrer">Proxy</a> with a <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Proxy/Proxy/construct" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><code>contruct</code> trap</a> that uses <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Reflect" rel="nofollow noreferrer">reflection</a> to build instances:</p>
<pre class="lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>class Rectangle {
  constructor(length, width) {
    this.length = length;
    this.width = width;
  }

  getArea() {
    return this.length * this.width;
  }

  static create(length, width) {
    return new Rectangle(length, width);
  }
}

let CurrentClass = Rectangle;

const proxied = new Proxy(Rectangle, {
  construct(target, args) {
    return Reflect.construct(CurrentClass, args);
  }
});

export { proxied as Rectangle };
</code></pre>
<p>We can now import <code>Rectangle</code> from this module, but every time we call <code>new Rectangle(...)</code> we're actually doing that by way of our <code>construct</code> proxy function.</p>
<p>Which means we can arbitrarily update the class:</p>
<pre class="lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>class Rectangle {
  // ...
}

let CurrentClass = Rectangle;
const rectangles = [];

export function updateRectangleClass(SomeNewClass) {
  CurrentClass = SomeNewClass;
  for (const r of rectangles) {
    Object.setPrototypeOf(instance, CurrentClass.prototype);
  }
}

const proxied = new Proxy(Rectangle, {
  construct(target, args) {
    const instance = Reflect.construct(CurrentClass, args);
    rectangles.push(instance);
    return instance;
  }
});

export { proxied as Rectangle };
</code></pre>
<p>And done: we can now change the Rectangle class as much as we want, with both <code>new Rectangle</code> as well as previously created instances all updating as needed. And of course, you can add more Proxy traps for things like static properties and methods, just implement what you need and off you go.</p>

Q: In Next.js App Router:, cookie set in server action is not available during initial client render A: <p>Server Actions update cookies for the <em>next request</em>, not the current render. That’s why the cookie isn’t available during the first client render.</p>
<pre><code>import { cookies } from 'next/headers';

export default function ThemeWidget() {
  const theme = cookies().get('theme')?.value ?? 'light';
  return &lt;div&gt;theme: {theme}&lt;/div&gt;;
}
</code></pre>

Q: How to implement JUnit 4 parameterized tests in JUnit 5? A: <h2><code>@ParameterizedClass</code></h2>
<p><a href="https://docs.junit.org/5.13.0/release-notes/index.html#release-notes-5.13.0-junit-jupiter-new-features-and-improvements" rel="nofollow noreferrer">JUnit Jupiter 5.13.0+</a> supports parameters at class level via annotation <a href="https://docs.junit.org/current/api/org.junit.jupiter.params/org/junit/jupiter/params/ParameterizedClass.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer">@ParameterizedClass</a>. All test methods within the class will be executed with the same parameters.</p>
<h3><code>@MethodSource</code></h3>
<p>Specify a method supplying the parameters.</p>
<pre class="lang-java prettyprint-override"><code>import java.util.List;

import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import org.junit.jupiter.params.Parameter;
import org.junit.jupiter.params.ParameterizedClass;
import org.junit.jupiter.params.provider.MethodSource;

@ParameterizedClass
@MethodSource(&quot;foosToTest&quot;)
class FooInvariantsTest {

    static List&lt;Foo&gt; foosToTest() {
        return List.of(new CsvFoo(), new SqlFoo(), new XmlFoo());
    }

    @Parameter
    Foo fooToTest;

    @Test
    void testInvariant1() {
        // ...
    }

    @Test
    void testInvariant2() {
        // ...
    }

}
</code></pre>
<h3><code>@FieldSource</code></h3>
<p>Alternatively a <a href="https://docs.junit.org/current/api/org.junit.jupiter.params/org/junit/jupiter/params/provider/FieldSource.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><code>FieldSource</code></a> can supply the parameters.</p>
<pre class="lang-java prettyprint-override"><code>import java.util.List;

import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import org.junit.jupiter.params.Parameter;
import org.junit.jupiter.params.ParameterizedClass;
import org.junit.jupiter.params.provider.FieldSource;

@ParameterizedClass
@FieldSource(&quot;foosToTest&quot;)
class FooInvariantsTest {

    static final List&lt;Foo&gt; foosToTest = List.of(new CsvFoo(), new SqlFoo(), new XmlFoo());

    @Parameter
    Foo fooToTest;

    @Test
    void testInvariant1() {
        // ...
    }

    @Test
    void testInvariant2() {
        // ...
    }

}
</code></pre>

Q: Getting Input without Blocking Mode in C A: <p>There is no cross-platform way.
On UNIX-like (UNIX,Linux,CYGWIN) or BSD-like (*BSD,MacOS,...) systems, you can check if there is data available with <code>ioctl</code>:</p>
<pre><code>#include &lt;sys/ioctl.h&gt;
int uartRead(void *data, ssize_t size) {
    int bytes = 0;
    ioctl(0, FIONREAD, &amp;bytes);
    if (!bytes) return 0;
    int result = read(0, data, size);
    return result;
}
</code></pre>
<p>With any POSIX-compiant compiler you can also use <code>poll</code> (but it's epsilon slower than ioctl, so on an emmbed system it's better to use <code>ioctl</code> when possible)</p>
<pre><code>#include &lt;poll.h&gt;
int uartRead(void *data, ssize_t size) {
    struct pollfd pollin;
    pollin.fd = 0; 
    pollin.events = POLLIN;
    poll(&amp;pollin, 1, 0);
    if (!(pollin.revents &amp; POLLIN)) return 0;
    int result = read(0, data, size);
    return result;
}
</code></pre>
<p>On Windows (which is the most popular non (UNIX/BSD)-like and non POSIX-compliant operating system), you can use the <code>conio.h</code> library</p>
<pre><code>#include &lt;conio.h&gt;
int uartRead(void *data, ssize_t size) {
    int result = 0;
    while (_kbhit() &amp;&amp; result &lt; size)
        data[result++] = getch();
    return result;
}
</code></pre>
<p>This unfortunantly doesn't do input buffering (doesn't wait for a the user to press enter), so we have to implement if ourselves (here is an example implementation using a linked list):</p>
<pre><code>#include &lt;conio.h&gt;
#include &lt;stdlib.h&gt;
struct character {
    char c;
    struct character* next;
};
struct {
   struct character* first;
   struct character* last;
   struct character* endl;
} inputbuf;
int uartRead(void* _data, ssize_t size) {
    while (_kbhit()) {
        if (inputbuf.last) inputbuf.last=inputbuf.last-&gt;next=(struct character*)calloc(1,sizeof(struct character));
        else inputbuf.last=inputbuf.first=(struct character*)calloc(1,sizeof(struct character));
        if ((inputbuf.last-&gt;c = getch())=='\n') inputbuf.endl=inputbuf.last;
    }
    if (!inputbuf.endl) return 0; 

    // we can do this because char is an 8-bit intiger on Windows
    char* data = (char*)_data;
    int result=0;
    while (result&lt;size) {
        data[result++]=inputbuf.first-&gt;c;
        struct character* oldfirst = inputbuf.first;
        inputbuf.first=inputbuf.first-&gt;next;
        if (oldfirst==inputbuf.endl) {
            if (oldfirst==inputbuf.last) inputbuf.last=NULL;
            free(inputbuf.endl);
            inputbuf.endl=NULL;
            break;
        }
        free(oldfirst);
    }
    return result;
}
</code></pre>
